<h1>RadzenDataGrid Hierarchy Bug Demonstration</h1>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <h4>Issue Description</h4>
    <p>
        This application demonstrates a bug in <code>RadzenDataGrid</code> that prevents nested tables 
        in a hierarchy from expanding properly when they are loaded dynamically from a collection of 
        <strong>record</strong> objects.
    </p>
    <p>
        The workaround is to use <strong>classes</strong> instead of records.
    </p>
</div>

<h2>Navigation</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <a href="/hierarchy-records"><strong>Records (Bug Demo)</strong></a> - 
        Shows the issue with C# record types where nested hierarchies may not expand properly
    </li>
    <li>
        <a href="/hierarchy-classes"><strong>Classes (Workaround)</strong></a> - 
        Shows that the same structure works correctly when using class types
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>Test Scenario</h2>
<p>Both pages display a three-level hierarchy:</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Departments</strong> - Top level</li>
    <li><strong>Employees</strong> - Nested under departments</li>
    <li><strong>Tasks</strong> - Nested under employees</li>
</ol>

<h2>Expected Behavior</h2>
<p>
    When clicking the expand arrow next to a Department row, you should see the Employees. 
    When clicking the expand arrow next to an Employee row, you should see their Tasks.
</p>

<h2>Current Behavior</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>With Records:</strong> The nested expansion may not work properly</li>
    <li><strong>With Classes:</strong> The nested expansion works as expected</li>
</ul>
